{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"37c0c96f-2caa-4edf-8049-5dd3d22045ee","content":"\n\n`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI `ContentPage` property — that's likely why it has no effect. You need platform-specific approaches for each OS:\n\n### iOS — disable safe area insets\n```xml\n<ContentPage \n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### Android — draw behind system bars\n.NET 10 enforces edge-to-edge on Android 15+, but MAUI **auto-pads** the page content to keep it out of system bar regions. To override that, use platform-specific code in your page:\n\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nprotected override void OnAppearing()\n{\n    base.OnAppearing();\n    if (Window?.Handler?.PlatformView is Android.App.Activity activity)\n    {\n        // Make system bars transparent\n        activity.Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        activity.Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    }\n    // Remove MAUI's automatic inset padding\n    Padding = new Thickness(0);\n}\n#endif\n```\n\n### Full XAML example\n```xml\n<ContentPage \n    xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n    xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n    Padding=\"0\"\n    x:Class=\"MyApp.PhotoViewerPage\">\n\n    <Image Source=\"{Binding PhotoSource}\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"`** — iOS ignores safe areas (notch, home indicator)\n- **`Padding=\"0\"`** — ensures no extra spacing (MAUI may re-apply it on Android, which is why the code-behind override helps)\n- **`Aspect=\"AspectFill\"`** — makes the image fill all available space, cropping if needed\n\nIf MAUI keeps resetting the padding on Android, you can also use a custom `PageHandler` to suppress the inset behavior more permanently:\n\n```csharp\n// In MauiProgram.cs\nbuilder.ConfigureMauiHandlers(handlers =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    Microsoft.Maui.Handlers.PageHandler.Mapper.AppendToMapping(\"NoInsets\", (handler, view) =>\n    {\n        if (view is PhotoViewerPage)\n            handler.PlatformView.SetFitsSystemWindows(false);\n    });\n#endif\n});\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"baa18bf7-469e-4826-ab16-54f9636b3fca","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI edge-to-edge display for a photo viewer. In .NET 10 (which aligns with MAUI 10), there were significant changes to how edge-to-edge/full-screen content works, particularly on Android.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI (.NET 9+), Android adopted edge-to-edge display by default. The key things to understand:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on `ContentPage` is an iOS concept - it controls the `SafeAreaLayoutGuide` on iOS. It doesn't affect Android.\n\n2. On Android in .NET 10 / MAUI 10, the app goes edge-to-edge by default (Android 15+ enforces this). \n\nHowever, the system still applies window insets padding to keep content from rendering behind system bars. To actually draw behind the status bar and navigation bar, I need to handle window insets properly. For iOS, I should use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"false\"` or `IgnoreSafeArea` on individual views to bypass safe area constraints. On Android, the approach involves configuring the app to draw behind system bars and then managing the insets manually. I'm realizing `SafeAreaEdges` might not be a standard MAUI property at all—they could be mixing it up with `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` or using something custom. For Android edge-to-edge behavior in .NET 9+, the approach has shifted, and I need to clarify what the actual platform-specific APIs are versus what MAUI abstracts. For Android, the approach differs between .NET 9 and .NET 10—in the newer version, edge-to-edge is enforced on Android 16+, so I need to handle the system bar padding through platform-specific configuration rather than just setting `Padding=\"0\"` on the page, since MAUI will override that automatically based on the system bars. I'm realizing that `SafeAreaEdges` likely doesn't exist as a standard MAUI property—the user might be mixing this up with another framework. The actual solution involves using platform-specific configuration: on iOS, I'd use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` in XAML, while on Android, I need to prevent MAUI from automatically padding around system bars, which typically requires platform-specific code to make the bars transparent and disable the automatic inset handling. I need to clarify what MAUI actually supports here—`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard property, so I should focus on the real solutions: using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` for iOS and handling Android's system bar insets through padding or platform-specific code to achieve true edge-to-edge rendering.","outputTokens":2694},"id":"1d3e235d-9bf1-4d2f-a412-4bd914fd1ceb","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:49:10.682Z","parentId":"897701a8-d303-4b09-a1bc-51b63740ed80"}
